t. So, instead of judging the suggestions, figure out the emotion that is driving them.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As you map all the expectations, pains and emotions, you start observing patterns and then you might revisit some of their suggestions and see which of those could be used within the overall context.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Let me cite an example from our experience</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">The Novatium affair</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Novatium was a low-cost computer with a simpler interface aimed at people who are relatively new to the world of computers. At the same time, the stakeholders didn\'t want to take the focus totally out of the users who are experienced. Our job was to redesign their existing OS.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We began our journey with User discussions. During our discussions, we figured out that some had really strong opinions about certain features and experiences. A large majority of them were not happy with the support, while some had issues with connectivity and missing features. Some said that the OS was looking easy but took a while to understand. But, none of them have explicitly complained about the style of UI. So, should we stop re-designing the UI because Users were not complaining or we should be, because we felt the UI was not \'beautiful\'? The answer is a big NO to both. You should never redesign because you feel that it is not okay, it should be driven by the expectations of the users. But then, no one is asking for it, you might say. Yes, none have \'explicitly\' asked for it, but does it mean that they do not have any problem at all? They did, and they have expressed about those. Take these,</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">The support complaints - they give us a a good insight into the issues pertaining to the entire aspect of support and the experience around it. We also can take a relook at the help provided within the OS. Also, we need to look at the real need that is driving the support expectation.</li>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">Maybe UI was not a big problem considering the other problems they were facing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, if he had judged the responses on their face value, we might have reached an unfavourable conclusion that could derail the design effort. We haven\'t done that, but did a detailed route-cause analysis to understand the core issues. In this effort, we have consciously involved the stakeholders and that did help us immensely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Conclusion</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">With all my experience, what I understood is, Users are extremely intelligent. They specifically know what they want and how they want. The only thing they do not know is, how to address them. It is us designers job to raise our hands and respond to the occasion.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, coming back to the opening quote, if the guy who made the statement did get a request for ‘faster horses’, then it is entirely up to him what to do with such a request. Whether to get into horse breeding or build carts with something that does a better job than a Horse. The users create the ideas; it is up to the presenter how well he can perceive the need and fulfil it.</p>','','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2016-07-18 00:55:33','2016-07-17 19:25:33','',86,'http://www.divami.com/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2016-07-18 00:56:36','2016-07-17 19:26:36','<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said faster horses</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><i>Allegedly said by Henry Ford, which seems very unlikely</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">I am uncomfortable with the essence of this statement. It appears to be hinting that users do not know what they want. I disagree with that thought.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As a designer, if you are expecting your users to articulate in precise terms what they expect, then you are not in the right job. Users can throw random thoughts stemmed ou