quest for ‘faster horses’, then it is entirely up to him what to do with such a request. Whether to get into horse breeding or build carts with something that does a better job. The smarter choice leads to a greater product revolution.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The users create the ideas; it is up to the presenter how well he can perceive the need and fulfil it.</p>','Users know what they need','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2016-07-18 15:38:31','2016-07-18 10:08:31','',86,'http://www.divami.com/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(126,1,'2016-07-18 15:40:28','2016-07-18 10:10:28','/*\nWelcome to Custom CSS!\n\nTo learn how this works, see http://wp.me/PEmnE-Bt\n*/\np.quote {\n	font-size: 20px;\n	font-weight: 100;\n	color: #999999;\n}','safecss','divami','inherit','closed','closed','','118-revision-v1','','','2016-07-18 15:40:28','2016-07-18 10:10:28','',118,'http://www.divami.com/blog/118-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(127,1,'2016-07-18 15:41:10','2016-07-18 10:11:10','<p class=\"quote\">If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said faster horses\r\n<i>Allegedly said by Henry Ford, which seems very unlikely</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">I am uncomfortable with the essence of this statement. It appears to be hinting that users do not know what they want. I disagree with that thought.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As a designer, if you are expecting your users to articulate in precise terms what they expect, then you are not in the right job. Users can throw random thoughts stemmed out of their needs, expectations and pains. Sometimes, these ideas can also sound radically drastic. It might be because they do not prefer to check the feasibility when they speak their mind. But, that\'s <span style=\"background-color: #f5f6f5;\">anyway </span>not their job. It is the job of the designer to sift through this information, juxtapose it onto the core product\'s context, validate the feasibility and deliver what could be the best.</p>\r\n