ass=\"p1\">Let me cite an example from our experience</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">The Novatium affair</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Novatium was a low-cost computer with a simpler interface aimed at people who are relatively new to the world of computers. At the same time, the stakeholders didn\'t want to take the focus totally out of the users who are experienced. Our job was to redesign their existing OS.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We began our journey with User discussions. During our discussions, we figured out that some had really strong opinions about certain features and experiences. A vast majority of them were not happy with the support, while some had issues with connectivity and missing features. Some said that the OS was looking easy, but it took a while for them to understand it. Having said that, none of them have explicitly complained about the style of UI. So, should we stop re-designing the UI because Users were not complaining or we should be, because we felt the UI was not \'beautiful\'? The answer is a big NO to both. You should never redesign because you feel that it is not okay, it should be driven by the expectations of the users. But then, no one is asking for it, you might say. Yes, none have \'explicitly\' asked for it, but does it mean that they do not have any problem at all? They did, and they have expressed about those. Consider these,</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">The support complaints - they give us a real insight into the issues about the entire aspect of support and the experience around it. We also can take a relook at the help provided by the OS. Also, we need to look at the real need that is driving the support expectation.</li>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">Maybe UI was not a big problem considering the other problems they were facing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, if we had judged the responses on their face value, we might have reached an unfavourable conclusion that could have derailed the design effort. We haven\'t done that b