rom our experience</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">The Novatium affair</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><a href=\"http://novatium.com/solutions.html?tabId=0\" target=\"_blank\">Novatium</a> is a low-cost computer with a simpler interface aimed at people who are relatively new to the world of computers. At the same time, the stakeholders didn\'t want to take the focus totally out of the users who are experienced. Our job was to redesign their existing OS.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We began our journey with User discussions. During our discussions, we figured out that some had really strong opinions about certain features and experiences. A vast majority of them were not happy with the support, while some had issues with connectivity and missing features. Some said that the OS was looking easy, but it took a while for them to understand it. Having said that, none of them have explicitly complained about the style of UI. So, should we stop re-designing the UI because Users were not complaining or we should be, because we felt the UI was not \'beautiful\'? The answer is a big NO to both. You should never redesign because you feel that it is not okay, it should be driven by the expectations of the users. But then, no one is asking for it, you might say. Yes, none have \'explicitly\' asked for it, but does it mean that they do not have any problem at all? They did, and they have expressed about those. Consider these,</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">The support complaints - they give us a real insight into the issues about the entire aspect of support and the experience around it. We also can take a relook at the help provided by the OS. Also, we need to look at the real need that is driving the support expectation.</li>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">Maybe UI was not a big problem considering the other problems they were facing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, if we had judged the responses on their face value, we might have reached an unfavourable conclusion that could have derailed the design effort. We haven\'t done that but did a detailed route-cause analysis to understand the core issues. In this endeavour, we have consciously involved the stakeholders, and that did help us immensely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Conclusion</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">With all my experience, what I understood is, Users are brilliant. They specifically know what they want and how they want. The only thing they do not know is, how to address them. It is us designers job to raise our hands and respond to the occasion.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Coming back to the opening quote; the responders are subtly telling that they need to travel quick, and they felt faster horses would help the cause. So, if the guy who made the statement did get a request for ‘faster horses’, then it is entirely up to him what to do with such a request. Whether to get into horse breeding or build carts with something that does a better job. The smarter choice leads to a greater product revolution.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The users create the ideas; it is up to the presenter how well he can perceive the need and fulfil it.</p>','Users know what they want','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2016-07-18 22:46:53','2016-07-18 17:16:53','',86,'http://www.divami.com/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2016-07-18 22:47:35','2016-07-18 17:17:35','<p class=\"quote\">If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said \'faster horses.\'\r\n<i class=\"author\"> - Allegedly said by Henry Ford. But, seems like he didn\'t!</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Whoever said that its essence makes me uncomfortable. It directly hints that users do not know what they want. I disagree with such a thought.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As a designer, if you are expecting your users to articulate in precise terms what they expect, then you are not in the right job. Users can throw random thoughts stemmed out of their needs, expectations and pains. Sometimes, these ideas can also sound radically drastic. It might be because they do not prefer to check the feasibility when they speak their mind. But, that\'s <span style=\"background-color: #f5f6f5;\">anyway </span>not their job. It is the job of the designer to sift through this information, juxtapose it onto the core product\'s context, validate the feasibility and deliver what could be the best.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Everybody understands design</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Us humans have always been very particular about our choices. Be it arranging different items in our home to getting dressed for an occasion, we <span style=\"background-color: #f5f6f5;\">have </span>always given importance to our choices. I prefer to call it as designing for oneself. We know what we like - the colors, arrangement of things et al. - and there is always an effort to make sure we get what we like. And we also know how to maneuver ourselves carefully through the lanes of our personal likes and dislikes while not falling into the traps of financial feasibilities. Pure user-centric design, I would say.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Respect every input of users and carefully validate</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The beauty of User Discussions is the eagerness that User\'s display. They have a point in everything about the context - right from the colour and style suggestions to the aspect of information flow. Not everyone might speak every emotion of theirs, but they do \'express.\' A Designer\'s job is to consciously to read all these expressions, verbal or non-verbal, and understand the underlying issue. A pertinent quality I observe among the designers is the aspect of critiquing the suggestions of the Users. This choice is not smart. Because a majority of their ideas are \'their\' solutions to the problems they face - there might not be a conscious thought about the other users at all. So, some of them might look a little off-beat. Instead of judging the suggestions, figure out the emotion that is driving them.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As you map all the expectations, pains and emotions, you start observing patterns and then you might revisit some of their suggestions and see which of those could be used within the overall context.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Let me cite an example from our experience</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">The Novatium affair</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><a href=\"http://novatium.com/solutions.html?tabId=0\">Novatium</a> is a low-cost computer with a simpler interface aimed at people who are relatively new to the world of computers. At the same time, the stakeholders didn\'t want to take the focus totally out of the users who are experienced. Our job was to redesign their existing OS.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We began our journey with User discussions. During our discussions, we figured out that some had really strong opinions about certain features and experiences. A vast majority of them were not happy with the support, while some had issues with connectivity and missing features. Some said that the OS was looking easy, but it took a while for them to understand it. Having said that, none of them have explicitly complained about the style of UI. So, should we stop re-designing the UI because Users were not complaining or we should be, because we felt the UI was not \'beautiful\'? The answer is a big NO to both. You should never redesign because you feel that it is not okay, it should be driven by the expectations of the users. But then, no one is asking for it, you might say. Yes, none have \'explicitly\' asked for it, but does it mean that they do not have any problem at all? They did, and they have expressed about those. Consider these,</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">The support complaints - they give us a real insight into the issues about the entire aspect of support and the experience around it. We also can take a relook at the help provided by the OS. Also, we need to look at the real need that is driving the support expectation.</li>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">Maybe UI was not a big problem considering the other problems they were facing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, if we had judged the responses on their face value, we might have reached an unfavourable conclusion that could have derailed the design effort. We haven\'t done that but did a detailed route-cause analysis to understand the core issues. In this endeavour, we have consciously involved the stakeholders, and that did help us immensely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Conclusion</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">With all my experience, what I understood is, Users are brilliant. They specifically know what they want and how they want. The only thing they do not know is, how to address them. It is us designers job to raise our hands and respond to the occasion.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Coming back to the opening quote; the responders are subtly telling that they need to travel quick, and they felt faster horses would help the cause. So, if the guy who made the statement did get a request for ‘faster horses’, then it is entirely up to him what to do with such a request. Whether to get into horse breeding or build carts with something that does a better job. The smarter choice leads to a greater product revolution.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The users create the ideas; it is up to the presenter how well he can perceive the need and fulfil it.</p>','Users know what they want','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2016-07-18 22:47:35','2016-07-18 17:17:35','',86,'http://www.divami.com/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2016-07-19 14:24:19','2016-07-19 08:54:19','<p class=\"quote\">If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said \'faster horses.\'\r\n<i class=\"author\"> - Allegedly said by Henry Ford. But, seems like he didn\'t!</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We don\'t know who created that, but its essence makes me uncomfortable. It directly hints that users do not know what they want. I disagree with such a thought.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">As a designer, if you are anticipating your users to articulate in precise terms what they expect, then you are not in the right job. Users can throw random thoughts stemmed out of their needs, expectations and pains. Sometimes, these ideas can also sound radically drastic. It might be because they do not care to check the feasibility when they speak their mind. But, that\'s <span style=\"background-color: #f5f6f5;\">anyway </span>not their job. It is the job of the designer to sift through this information, juxtapose it onto the core product\'s context, validate the feasibility and deliver what could be the best.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Everybody understands design</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Us humans have always been very particular about our choices. Be it arranging different items in our home to getting dressed for an occasion, we <span style=\"background-color: #f5f6f5;\">have </span>always given importance to our choices. I prefer to call it as designing for oneself. We know what we like - the colors, arrangement of things et al. - and there is always an effort to make sure we get what we like. And we also know how to maneuver ourselves carefully through the lanes of our personal likes and dislikes while not falling into the traps of financial feasibilities. Pure user-centric design, I would say.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Respect every user input and validate them with respect</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The beauty of User Discussions is the eagerness that User\'s display. They have a point in everything about the context - right from the colour and style suggestions to the aspect of information flow. Not everyone might speak every emotion of theirs, but they do \'express.\' A Designer\'s job is to consciously to read all these expressions, verbal or non-verbal, and understand the underlying issue. A pertinent trait I observe among the designers is the aspect of criticising the suggestions of the Users. This choice is not smart. Because a majority of their ideas are \'their\' solutions to the problems they face - there might not be a conscious thought about the other users at all. So, some of them might look a little off-beat. Instead of judging the suggestions, figure out the emotion that is driving them. And it is those emotions that you need to respond to.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Let me cite an example from our experience</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">The Novatium affair</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><a href=\"http://novatium.com/solutions.html?tabId=0\">Novatium</a> is a low-cost computer with a simpler interface aimed at people who are relatively new to the world of computers. At the same time, the stakeholders didn\'t want to take the focus totally out of the users who are experienced. Our job was to redesign their existing OS.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We began our journey with User discussions. During our discussions, we figured out that some users had really strong opinions about certain features and experiences. A vast majority of them were not happy with the support, while some had issues with the connectivity and missing features. Some said that the OS, at the outset, was looking easy but it took a while for them to get used to. But, none of them had explicitly complained about the style or graphics. So, should we stop re-designing the UI because Users were not complaining or should we because we felt the UI was not \'beautiful\'? The answer is a big NO to both. You should never redesign because you feel that it is not okay, it should be driven by the expectations of the users. But then, no one is asking for it, you might say. Yes, none have \'explicitly\' asked for it, but does it mean that they do not have any problem at all? They did, and they have expressed about those. Check these,</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">The support issues - the users did give us an insight into the issues about the entire aspect of support and the experience around it. For this, we can investigate and figure out which compelling need is driving them to look for support. We can check if the in-system help is work or not. We can even check if the delay in response is causing the trouble or if there is no response to the calls at all. And a lot of finer aspects like that.</li>\r\n 	<li class=\"p1\">Alternatively, they might not have felt that UI was a big problem in comparison to the other problems they were facing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">So, if we had judged the responses on their face value, we might have reached an unfavourable conclusion that could have derailed the design effort. We haven\'t done that but did a detailed route-cause analysis to understand the core issues. In this endeavour, we have consciously involved the stakeholders, and that did help us immensely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\">Conclusion</h4>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Users are brilliant! They specifically know what they want and how they want. The only thing they do not know is, how to address such \'wants\'. It is us designers\' job to raise our hands and respond to the occasion.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Coming back to the opening quote; the responders are subtly telling that they need to travel quick, and they felt faster horses might help. So, if the guy who made the statement did get a request for ‘faster horses’, then it is entirely up to him what to do with such a request. Whether to get into horse breeding or build carts with something that does a better job. The smarter choice leads to a greater product revolution.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The users create paths to the ideas; it is up to the presenter how well he can pick those paths and fulfil the needs with great designs.</p>','Users know what they want','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2016-07-19 14:24:19','2016-07-19 08:54:19','',86,'http://www.divami.com/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(145,1,'2016-07-19 14:25:01','2016-07-19 08:55:01','<p class=\"quote\">If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said \'faster horse