yClassName()’, </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">It’ll return an </span><b>array-like object</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> (node list, not an array) of all child elements which have all of the given class names.\r\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">But what if i want to iterate over that </span><b>array-like object</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> using array methods? Directly you can’t use array method such as </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">forEach, map..etc.\r\n</span></i>In that case, what I do is:\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;pre&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;code&gt;\r\n</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.prototype.forEach.call(elems, node =&gt; console.log(node));\r\n</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/code&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n</span>It’s a bit lengthy (of Course, not much).\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Using the new method </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.from(), </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">which was introduced in ES6, you can convert an array-like or iterable object to an array.\r\n</span>&lt;pre&gt;\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;code&gt;\r\n</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">var elements = document.getElementsByClassName(‘***’); // returns an array-like object\r\n</span></i><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.from(elements); // returns an array with html nodes\r\n</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/code&gt;\r\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n</span>These new methods reduce our efforts a bit. Thanks for ES6 release.\r\n\r\nHappy Coding :)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<pre>[code]\r\nhello: {\r\n//***\r\n}\r\n[/code]</pre>','Why never use new Array in Javascript?','','inherit','closed','closed','','330-revision-v1','','','2017-09-22 15:22:16','2017-09-22 09:52:16','',330,'http://www.divami.com/blog/330-revision-v1/',0,'revis