weight: 400\">Array(7) creates an empty array with a length property of 7</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> (Note: this implies an array of 7 empty slots, not slots with actual undefined values).</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;code&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.of(7); // an array with one element i.e. [7]</span></i>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.of(1, 2, 3); // an array with three elements i.e. [1, 2, 3]</span></i>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/code&gt;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">\r\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">As a web developer, you may regularly do </span><a href=\"https://plainjs.com/javascript/manipulation/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">DOM manipulation</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">. When you use ‘</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">document.getElementsByClassName()’, </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">It’ll return an </span><b>array-like object</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> (node list, not an array) of all child elements which have all of the given class names.\r\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">But what if i want to iterate over that </span><b>array-like object</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> using array methods? Directly you can’t use array method such as </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">forEach, map..etc.\r\n</span></i>In that case, what I do is:\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;pre&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;code&gt;\r\n</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.prototype.forEach.call(elems, node =&gt; console.log(node));\r\n</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/code&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n</span>It’s a bit lengthy (of Course, not much).\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Using the new method </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Array.from(), <