ie, we need to rotate it by <code>first pie\'s percentage + second pie\'s percentage</code>. Since all pie diagrams start with a 90^\\circ off, it is better to rotate all these <code>circles</code> by -90^\\circ or 270^\\circ maybe through a parent element i.e a <code>group</code> tag.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre><code>&lt;svg&gt;\r\n    &lt;g class=\"circles\"&gt;\r\n        &lt;circle class=\"pie-one\" cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"50\"&gt;&lt;/circle&gt;\r\n        &lt;circle class=\"pie-two\" cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"50\"&gt;&lt;/circle&gt;\r\n        &lt;circle class=\"pie-three\" cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"50\"&gt;&lt;/circle&gt;\r\n    &lt;/g&gt;\r\n&lt;/svg&gt;\r\n\r\n.circles {\r\n    transform: rotate(-90deg);\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<p>As in the real scenario, the circles could be dynamic, it is better to generate the circles through JavaScript and pass the percentage values through an object. I got my donut chart by following the above steps, hope it will be helpful to you as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"codepen\">See the Pen <a href=\"https://codepen.io/Mr_Green/pen/ZabqPM/\">Hollow pie chart</a> by venkateshwar (<a href=\"https://codepen.io/Mr_Green\">@Mr_Green</a>) on <a href=\"https://codepen.io\">CodePen</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&lt;hr\r\n','Usage of SVG stroke dasharray','','inherit','closed','closed','','374-revision-v1','','','2018-02-02 18:25:52','2018-02-02 12:55:52','',374,'http://www.divami.com/blog/374-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(377,21,'2018-02-02 18:30:39','2018-02-02 13:00:39','','Screen Shot 2018-02-02 at 6.29.56 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2018-02-02-at-6-29-56-pm','','','2018-02-02 18:30:39','2018-02-02 13:00:39','',374,'http://www.divami.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Screen-Shot-2018-02-02-at-6.29.56-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(378,21,'2018-02-02 18:30:47','2018-02-02 13:00:47','<p>I am still new to SVG and its quite exciting whenever I come to know more about it. Recently, I did an experiment with <code>s